AB  - It is very difficult to understand peace building and reconciliation among parties formerly in conflict and war, if one ignores the role that perceptions of the past play in interpretations of these events and, consequently, in the social-political developments of the postwar society. This article explores the impact of war remembrance in the young populatidn of Kosovo, raising the question of how these experiences influence their political attitudes particularly regarding identity building and ethnic relations. It outlines the emergence and presence of postwar narratives and memorialization by political forces along lines of ethno-national belonging, thus resulting in contested memories, failure of transitional justice and lack of reconciliation. The research explores the impact of socio-economic conditions in the political attitudes of young adults; nevertheless, it argues that youth - through civic education - has a potential to overcome ethnic divisions by promoting an appropriate culture of remembrance and reconciliation of the Kosovar society.
